==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Seem
<hw>Seem</hw> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧m)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Seemed</conjf> <pr>(s⟦emac⟧md)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Seeming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>semen</ets> to seem, to become, befit, AS. <ets>s⟦emac⟧man</ets> to
satisfy, pacify; akin to Icel. <ets>saema</ets> to honor, to bear with,
conform to, <ets>saemr</ets> becoming, fit, <ets>s⟦omac⟧ma</ets> to
beseem, to befit, <ets>sama</ets> to beseem, <ets>semja</ets> to
arrange, settle, put right, Goth. <ets>samjan</ets> to please, and to E.
<ets>same</ets>. The sense is probably due to the adj.
<ets>seemly</ets>. ⟦root⟧191. See <er>Same</er>, <pos>a.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Seemly</er>.]</ety> <def>To appear, or to appear to be; to have a
show or semblance; to present an appearance; to look; to strike one's
apprehension or fancy as being; to be taken as.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧It now
<xex>seemed</xex> probable.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou picture of what thou <qex>seem'st</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All <qex>seemed</qex> well pleased; all <qex>seemed</qex>, but
were not all.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is a way which <qex>seemeth</qex> right unto a man; but the
end thereof are the ways of death.</q> <rj><qau>Prov. xiv.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>It seems</b></col>, <cd>it appears; it is understood as
true; it is said.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A prince of Italy, <qex>it seems</qex>, entertained his mistress
on a great lake.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To appear; look.</syn> -- <usage><er>Seem</er>,
<er>Appear</er>. To <xex>appear</xex> has reference to a thing's being
presented to our view; as, the sun <xex>appears</xex>; to
<xex>seem</xex> is connected with the idea of <xex>semblance</xex>, and
usually implies an inference of our mind as to the probability of a
thing's being so; as, a storm <xex>seems</xex> to be coming. ⟦ldquo⟧The
story <xex>appears</xex> to be true,⟦rdquo⟧ means that the facts, as
presented, go to show its truth; ⟦ldquo⟧the story <xex>seems</xex> to be
true,⟦rdquo⟧ means that it has the semblance of being so, and we infer
that it is true. ⟦ldquo⟧His first and principal care being to
<xex>appear</xex> unto his people such as he would have them be, and to
be such as he <xex>appeared</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Sir P.
Sidney.</au></usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><it>Ham.</it> Ay, madam, it is common.⟦br⟧
<it>Queen</it>. If it be,⟦br⟧
Why <qex>seems</qex> it so particular with thee?⟦br⟧
<it>Ham.</it> <qex>Seems</qex>, madam! Nay, it is; I know not
⟦ldquo⟧<qex>seems</qex>.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Seem
<hw>Seem</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To befit; to beseem.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Seemer</ent>⟦br⟧
